Phloem ï‚· Bidirectional vessel ï‚· Contains sieve elements which allow sugars to pass from one cell to next downwards  ï‚· Contains companion cells which provide energy for active transport of sugars all over plant.  ï‚· Translocation moves organic molecules (sugars, amino acids) from source to sink.  ï‚· Phloem vessels still have cross walls called sieve plates that contain pores.  ï‚· Companion cells actively load sucrose into the phloem. ï‚· Water follows high solute in phloem by osmosis. A positive pressure potential develops moving mass of phloem sap forward. ï‚· Phloem still contains small amount of cytoplasm along the walls but the organelle content is greatly reduced. ï‚· Companion cells actively unload (ATP used) the organic molecules {#
