 Chemical Digestion ï‚· Where enzymes are used to break down large insoluble substances such as proteins into smaller soluble substances like amino acids so that they can be absorbed. ï‚· Amylase: breaks down starch into maltose, it is produced in the pancreas (but also in the salivary gland) ï‚· Protease: breaks down proteins to peptides (done by pepsin) then into amino acids (done by trypsin). Pepsin comes from the stomach and trypsin comes from the pancreas. ï‚· Lipase: breaks down lipids into fatty acids and glycerol, produced by the pancreas. ï‚· Hydrochloric acid in gastric juice: o Denaturing enzymes in harmful microorganisms in food o Giving the optimum pH for pepsin activity {#
[7.12]
 Absorption ï‚· Movement of digested food molecules through wall of the intestine into the blood or lymph. ï‚· The small intestine is the region for absorption of digested food. ï‚· The small intestine is folded into many villi which increase the surface area for absorption. One villus will have tiny folds on the cells on its outside called microvilli.  ï‚· More surface area means more absorption can happen ï‚· Capillary: transports glucose and amino acids 
ï‚· Vein: delivers absorbed products to liver via hepatic portal vein. ï‚· Gland: produces enzymes ï‚· Lacteal: absorbs fatty acid and glycerol ï‚· Epithelium: only one cell thick for faster transport. The cells of the epithelium are folded to form microvilli.  ï‚· Small intestine and colon absorb water  o The small intestine absorbs 5â€“10 dm3 per day  o The colon absorbs 0.3â€“0.5 dm3 per day 

