Pathway Taken By Water ï‚· Water enters root hair cell from moist soil via osmosis because water potential is higher in soil than in cytoplasm. ï‚· Water passes through the cortex cells by osmosis but mostly by â€œsuctionâ€. ï‚· Water and minerals are forced to cross the endodermis. ï‚· Water enters xylem then leaves when it gets to mesophyll cells {#
[8.4]
Transpiration ï‚· Transpiration: evaporation of water at surfaces of the mesophyll cells followed by loss of water vapour from plant leaves, through stomata. ï‚· Water leaves mesophyll cells, into air spaces created by irregular shape of spongy mesophyll cells, then diffuses out of the stomata. ï‚· Wilting: occurs if water loss is greater than water uptake â€“ cells become flaccid, tissues become limp and plant no longer supported {#
[8.5]
Uptake of Water ï‚· Caused by water loss in leaves which lowers its water potential  ï‚· Water moves from xylem to leaf tissues via osmosis ï‚· Water moves up the stem in the xylem due to tension (because of cohesion of water molecules to each other) caused by water loss from the leaves  ï‚· Ends with the gain of water through roots ï‚· This upward flow of water is called the transpiration stream {#
[8.6]
Factors Affecting Rate of Transpiration ï‚· Temperature: higher temperatures increase waterholding capacity of air and increases transpiration rate ï‚· Humidity: low humidity increases water potential gradient between leaf and atmosphere ïœ increasing transpiration rate ï‚· Light intensity: high light intensity causes stomata to open (to allow more photosynthesis) which causes increase in transpiration 
