ï‚· Pulmonary artery: carries deoxygenated blood from right ventricle to lungs ï‚· Septum: separates left and right sides of the heart ï‚· Pulmonary vein: carry oxygenated blood from lungs to left atrium ï‚· Left atrium: collect oxygenated blood and pump it to left ventricle ï‚· Left ventricle: pumps oxygenated blood to the body via the aorta ï‚· Aorta: carries oxygenated blood from left ventricle to rest of body ï‚· Tricuspid and bicuspid valves: prevent backflow of blood into the atria when ventricles contract (atria ventricular valves) ï‚· Pulmonary and aortic valves: prevent backflow of blood from the arteries into the ventricles (semi-lunar valves) {#
[9.3]
Cardiac Cycle 
   Cardiac diastole: all chambers are relaxed, and blood flows into the heart Atrial systole, ventricular diastole: atria contract, pushing blood into the ventricles Atrial diastole, ventricular systole: after atria relax, ventricles contract, pushing blood out of heart ï‚· Physical activity makes the heart beat more quickly and more deeply, for an increased circulation of blood so that more oxygen and glucose can get to the muscles. 
