ECG Trace ï‚· The electrical activity of the heart can be monitored by the electrocardiogram, pulse rate and listening to the sounds of the valves closing ï‚· Physical activity makes the heart beat more quickly and more deeply, for an increased circulation of blood so that more oxygen and glucose can get to the muscle 
{#
[9.5]
Coronary Heart Disease ï‚· Coronary artery becomes blocked, interrupting the supply of blood to the heart muscle.  
ï‚· The heart muscle cells are deprived of oxygen & glucose, and poisonous wastes such as lactic acid build up.  ï‚· Part of the heart muscle stops contracting, causing a heart attack ï‚· Caused by stress, smoking, poor diet, poor lifestyle & genetically ï‚· Can be prevented by not smoking, avoiding fatty food and exercising regularly ï‚· Treated by aspirin and surgery (stents, angioplasty and by-pass) {#
[9.6]
Arteries, Veins and Capillaries  VESSEL FUNCTION STRUCTURE 
ARTERY 
ï‚· Transport high pressure blood away from heart 
ï‚· Elastic walls expand and relax as blood is forced out; causes pulse  ï‚· Thick walls withstand high pressure ï‚· Rings of muscle narrow or widen artery to control blood flow. 
VEIN 
ï‚· Transport low pressure blood to the heart 
ï‚· Valves prevent backflow of blood.  ï‚· Blood is at low pressure, but nearby muscles squeeze veins and help push blood to the heart  ï‚· Large diameter and thin walls reduce resistance to flow of blood 
CAPILLARY 
ï‚· Allow substances to diffuse into cells 
ï‚· One cell thick walls for easy diffusion ï‚· Highly branched; large surface area  ï‚· Capillary beds constantly supplied with fresh blood, so diffusion occurs ï‚· Useful substances move out of plasma of capillaries into tissue fluid (fluid in between cells in tissues)  ï‚· Cells need oxygen and nutrients, and produce waste products such as CO2 & useful products such as hormone ï‚· Capillaries are constantly supplied with new blood, otherwise diffusion could not occur ï‚· Lungs â†’ heart = Pulmonary vein ï‚· Liver â†’ heart  = Hepatic vein ï‚· Kidneys â†’ heart  = Renal vein ï‚· Heart â†’ Lungs  = Pulmonary artery ï‚· Heart â†’ Liver  = Hepatic artery ï‚· Heart â†’ Kidneys  = Renal artery 
